WEBVTT

00:03.371 --> 00:06.238
(whispering to self)
Okay, 205.

00:06.240 --> 00:07.973
Hey, by the way,
no pressure

00:07.975 --> 00:09.541
if you want to bail
at any point tonight.

00:09.543 --> 00:10.909
I know that
we had other plans.

00:10.911 --> 00:12.611
Emily,
it's totally fine.

00:12.613 --> 00:14.413
We can hang out
and ruin stuff any night.

00:14.415 --> 00:16.882
But it's not every day
that your old college roommate

00:16.884 --> 00:18.717
comes to town,
come on!

00:18.719 --> 00:20.319
Yeah.

00:20.321 --> 00:23.489
It'll be nice
to catch up, I guess.

00:24.992 --> 00:26.992
It's not that
I don't want to see her.

00:26.994 --> 00:29.061
I just...
I don't really know

00:29.063 --> 00:30.529
if we have anything
in common anymore,

00:30.531 --> 00:32.464
you know?

00:32.466 --> 00:34.333
Becks has always been

00:34.335 --> 00:37.403
a lot more...
fun than me.

00:37.405 --> 00:39.938
Oh, yeah, people say that
about me all the time, so.

00:39.940 --> 00:43.175
Like, when she goes out,
she goes out hard.

00:43.177 --> 00:45.344
Although, now that
we're in our thirties,

00:45.346 --> 00:47.346
I'm sure
she's probably--

00:47.348 --> 00:49.214
(gasps)
Emilicious!

00:49.216 --> 00:50.916
Becksalicious!

00:50.918 --> 00:53.085
(screaming)
(laughing)

00:53.087 --> 00:54.887
Is this your friend
you were talking about?

00:54.889 --> 00:56.688
Hi, Becks!
I like how loud you are.

00:56.690 --> 00:59.058
Ha-ha! Thank you!
He's adorable.

00:59.060 --> 01:01.760
Okay, you guys, I'm still
getting ready, so come on in.

01:01.762 --> 01:03.328
I just need
to shave really quick.

01:03.330 --> 01:04.463
I had to skip
this morning,

01:04.465 --> 01:06.098
and I feel like
such a troll person.

01:06.100 --> 01:08.867
Huh! A hundred years ago,
people never shaved that much.

01:08.869 --> 01:10.536
It's a pretty
fascinating history.

01:10.538 --> 01:13.372
Oh, yeah, the history
of shaving is bonkers.

01:13.374 --> 01:15.107
Okay.

01:15.109 --> 01:16.375
So, what is it?

01:16.377 --> 01:19.878
Wait, you...
want to hear about it?

01:19.880 --> 01:21.513
Sure, just talk to me
in the bathroom

01:21.515 --> 01:22.981
while I'm finishing up.

01:22.983 --> 01:24.316
Emily, you wanna
do the honors?

01:24.318 --> 01:27.419
Yeah-- Becks,
I'm Emily Axford.

01:27.421 --> 01:29.321
That's Adam Conover.

01:29.323 --> 01:32.658
And this is
"Adam and Emily
Ruin Everything."

01:32.660 --> 01:35.327
¶¶

01:35.329 --> 01:36.795
(beep)
(scream)

01:36.797 --> 01:38.130
Closed Captions Provided by
truTV

01:42.336 --> 01:43.902
Sorry, guys,
I'll just be a few.

01:43.904 --> 01:46.638
I don't wanna scare any children
with these sasquatch legs.

01:46.640 --> 01:50.509
Yep, people definitely get
judgey about women's leg hair.

01:50.511 --> 01:52.878
But the fascinating thing
about shaving is

01:52.880 --> 01:55.047
almost no one did it
regularly at home

01:55.049 --> 01:58.150
until about a hundred years ago.

01:58.152 --> 02:00.986
What the (bleep), Emily?
Is this some sort of Purge shit?

02:00.988 --> 02:02.621
Oh, no no no,
don't worry.

02:02.623 --> 02:04.056
Me and Adam do this
all the time.

02:04.058 --> 02:07.226
Before the safety razor was
invented in the early 1900s,

02:07.228 --> 02:10.929
shaving with a straight razor
was a dangerous chore.

02:10.931 --> 02:13.031
So, most men either
went to a barber

02:13.033 --> 02:14.633
or didn't shave at all.

02:14.635 --> 02:17.503
No!... I can't do it.

02:17.505 --> 02:18.737
I've got a family.

02:18.739 --> 02:20.172
But all that changed

02:20.174 --> 02:22.207
when a man named
King Camp Gillette

02:22.209 --> 02:24.910
invented the first
disposable razor blade.

02:24.912 --> 02:26.111
Here, my good man,

02:26.113 --> 02:28.747
buy one of my safe,
disposable razors.

02:28.749 --> 02:30.415
Shaving your beard
will be such a breeze,

02:30.417 --> 02:31.717
you'll do it every day.

02:33.487 --> 02:35.053
Huh!

02:35.055 --> 02:36.889
Barely cut myself at all.

02:36.891 --> 02:38.690
The razors were
relatively cheap,

02:38.692 --> 02:42.027
but you'd have to keep
re-buying new blades.

02:42.029 --> 02:43.662
Refills cost extra,

02:43.664 --> 02:46.231
and you'll need
a new one every few weeks

02:46.233 --> 02:47.666
for the rest
of your life.

02:47.668 --> 02:49.701
But wait,
there's more.

02:49.703 --> 02:51.303
There is?
Oh, yeah.

02:51.305 --> 02:53.605
Gillette's real scam wasn't
getting people hooked

02:53.607 --> 02:55.274
on his replacement products,

02:55.276 --> 02:58.443
it was convincing women
that they had to shave too,

02:58.445 --> 03:00.245
for the first time
in history.

03:00.247 --> 03:01.914
And that story is--

03:01.916 --> 03:04.249
Super-messed up?
Heck yeah, it is!

03:04.251 --> 03:05.517
Oh.

03:05.519 --> 03:08.587
Up until 1920, most women
didn't shave at all.

03:08.589 --> 03:10.522
It was so unheard of that,

03:10.524 --> 03:12.758
when a teen girl cut
her legs shaving,

03:12.760 --> 03:14.993
it made national news.

03:14.995 --> 03:17.196
But all that changed
when old King Camp Gillette

03:17.198 --> 03:20.032
and the shaving industry started
thinking about how to expand

03:20.034 --> 03:21.900
to the disposable
razor business.

03:21.902 --> 03:24.203
Of course! Women!

03:24.205 --> 03:25.904
The other half
of the population.

03:25.906 --> 03:27.105
(snaps)

03:27.107 --> 03:29.942
But since most women
don't have beards,

03:29.944 --> 03:31.743
the shaving industry
had to convince women

03:31.745 --> 03:34.913
that they even had body hair
that needed shaving.

03:34.915 --> 03:38.750
So they whipped up some
manipulative advertising.

03:38.752 --> 03:41.653
First ads falsely claimed
that, in Europe,

03:41.655 --> 03:44.289
being hairless
was all the rage.

03:44.291 --> 03:48.860
Shaving your underarms is the
height of sophistication in...

03:48.862 --> 03:51.964
uh, "Franland" and "Spaintugal."

03:51.966 --> 03:54.600
Then, they pushed
the explicit message

03:54.602 --> 03:57.736
that women should be ashamed
of their armpit hair.

03:57.738 --> 04:00.639
But why would women's magazines
let advertisers

04:00.641 --> 04:02.007
say this junk to women?

04:02.009 --> 04:03.875
(woman)
Because that
was the whole point.

04:03.877 --> 04:05.510
(Emily)
Becks, this is
Rebecca Herzig,

04:05.512 --> 04:08.880
the author of "Plucked:
A History of Hair Removal."

04:08.882 --> 04:10.716
Becks, the reason
that these magazines

04:10.718 --> 04:13.418
didn't have any scruples about
shaming women into shaving

04:13.420 --> 04:17.256
in those days was because
that was pretty much
the whole point of the industry:

04:17.258 --> 04:18.957
getting women to buy things.

04:18.959 --> 04:21.893
Millions of women around the
globe trusted these magazines

04:21.895 --> 04:24.496
for advice, especially
as more and more young women

04:24.498 --> 04:27.266
were moving into cities and
living their lives cut off

04:27.268 --> 04:28.367
from their families.

04:28.369 --> 04:30.769
And publishers exploited
that trust,

04:30.771 --> 04:32.471
selling it off
to advertisers

04:32.473 --> 04:34.172
so that they could try
to convince women

04:34.174 --> 04:36.541
that if only they
bought their products

04:36.543 --> 04:38.944
all their problems
would be solved.

04:38.946 --> 04:41.780
And obviously making women think
that there was something wrong

04:41.782 --> 04:44.182
with their arm pit hair
was only the beginning.

04:44.184 --> 04:48.186
As fashion and culture evolved
to let women show more skin,

04:48.188 --> 04:51.923
they were also expected
to shave more skin.

04:51.925 --> 04:53.659
¶¶

04:53.661 --> 04:56.595
During the silk and nylon
rations of World War II,

04:56.597 --> 04:59.498
going stocking free
was considered patriotic.

04:59.500 --> 05:02.634
So long as you were
also hair free.

05:02.636 --> 05:05.237
If I don't shave my legs,
we'll lose the war.

05:05.239 --> 05:08.206
(Emily)
And when the bikini
was born in 1946,

05:08.208 --> 05:10.008
so was the bikini line.

05:10.010 --> 05:12.110
The only thing worse
than tan lines

05:12.112 --> 05:13.779
is a hair line.

05:13.781 --> 05:15.080
At least that's what
all the boys are saying

05:15.082 --> 05:17.049
at Makeout Beach.

05:17.051 --> 05:19.217
And with the rise of porn
in the '70s,

05:19.219 --> 05:22.487
women started getting pressured
to go all the way bare...

05:22.489 --> 05:23.655
(whispers)
down there.

05:23.657 --> 05:25.090
Well, all right!

05:25.092 --> 05:27.426
You ladies ready for some
inescapable cultural pressure

05:27.428 --> 05:31.029
to conform to what
I think is sexy?

05:31.031 --> 05:33.899
Yeah, no!
We're not gonna
show that, so...

05:33.901 --> 05:38.036
And American culture hit peak
hair removal in the year 2000

05:38.038 --> 05:40.305
when an entire episode
of "Sex and the City"

05:40.307 --> 05:43.842
was dedicated to...
the Brazilian wax.

05:43.844 --> 05:46.478
<i> I feel like one of those</i>
<i> freakin' hairless dogs.</i>

05:46.480 --> 05:49.147
<i> It's an esthetic thing.</i>
<i> Everyone goes bare out here.</i>

05:49.149 --> 05:51.383
I'm such an Elizabeth.

05:51.385 --> 05:53.085
Not a character, Adam.

05:53.087 --> 05:58.056
The cultural pressure
to shave is still very real.

05:58.058 --> 05:59.558
The average American woman

05:59.560 --> 06:03.028
spends almost $200 per year
on hair removal.

06:03.030 --> 06:06.064
And here's the kicker--
Women's shaving products

06:06.066 --> 06:10.268
cost more than men's even though
the only thing that's different

06:10.270 --> 06:12.938
is the packaging.

06:12.940 --> 06:14.806
It's called the pink tax.

06:14.808 --> 06:17.275
Seriously?
That's ridiculous.
Yup.

06:17.277 --> 06:19.177
But what's even
more ridiculous

06:19.179 --> 06:21.079
is that the marketing strategy
of making women

06:21.081 --> 06:23.315
think they need
to buy things to fix themself

06:23.317 --> 06:25.217
is still being used today!

06:26.253 --> 06:28.220
We see it in beauty products,

06:28.222 --> 06:32.424
diet foods and drinks,
even office supplies.

06:32.426 --> 06:35.927
But the reason shaving,
in particular,
really pisses me off

06:35.929 --> 06:39.164
is that most people
expect women to do it.

06:39.166 --> 06:41.333
Gillette and his cronies
convinced everyone

06:41.335 --> 06:44.269
that it's the friggin'
end of the world if a woman
has any body hair.

06:44.271 --> 06:49.074
So, even though I think
it's a complete waste of time,
I still usually do it.

06:49.076 --> 06:52.377
Fascinating and depressing.
Solid ruin, Em.

06:52.379 --> 06:53.478
Thank you.

06:53.480 --> 06:55.480
Yeah, I truly
never thought twice

06:55.482 --> 06:56.848
about shaving before now,

06:56.850 --> 07:00.385
but it really is such
pointless bullshit.

07:02.156 --> 07:05.624
But I already did this one
so I might as well even it out.

07:05.626 --> 07:06.858
Go with my blessing.

07:06.860 --> 07:09.027
Oh, hey, Em.
Are you bringing
a purse tonight?

07:09.029 --> 07:10.228
I don't want to carry
one in the club,

07:10.230 --> 07:11.730
but I need
somewhere to put my stuff.

07:11.732 --> 07:13.398
They can't fit
in your pockets?

07:13.400 --> 07:16.601
Oh, a lot of women's clothing
doesn't even have pockets.

07:16.603 --> 07:19.638
And there's a crazy history
behind that too.

07:19.640 --> 07:21.139
Oh, boy!

07:24.445 --> 07:26.745
Em, you ready to dance
our frickin' butts off?

07:26.747 --> 07:28.346
Oh, yeah...

07:30.818 --> 07:34.820
Love how loud it is and all
the strangers touching me.

07:34.822 --> 07:36.621
Emily, will you put
my stuff in your purse?

07:36.623 --> 07:38.690
I don't want it to jingle
jangle while I dance.

07:38.692 --> 07:40.292
Oh, I didn't bring one.

07:40.294 --> 07:42.127
I just stuffed everything
in my bra.

07:42.129 --> 07:44.196
Adam, you have pockets,
you can carry all of our stuff.

07:44.198 --> 07:47.632
Here are my keys,
phone, wallet, bronzer.

07:47.634 --> 07:49.568
Thank you.
What about your pockets?

07:49.570 --> 07:50.902
Oh, I don't have any.

07:50.904 --> 07:52.671
I guess it would mess with the
line of the dress or whatever.

07:52.673 --> 07:55.040
Oh, no.
Actually, the real reason

07:55.042 --> 07:56.741
women's clothing doesn't have
practical pockets

07:56.743 --> 08:00.579
is because of centuries
of sexism and classism, and...

08:00.581 --> 08:02.280
Sorry, Adam,
please hold my stuff too.

08:02.282 --> 08:04.616
Eh?!

08:04.618 --> 08:06.318
(crowd cheering)

08:06.320 --> 08:09.788
When pockets first became
popular in the 18th century,

08:09.790 --> 08:12.190
they were fraught
with political symbolism.

08:12.192 --> 08:14.159
And only for men.

08:14.161 --> 08:16.361
As men's fashion trended
away from tights

08:16.363 --> 08:18.430
and more towards
something closer to pants,

08:18.432 --> 08:19.965
two styles emerged:

08:19.967 --> 08:22.534
for the wealthy man,
tight fitting culottes

08:22.536 --> 08:24.402
without practical pockets

08:24.404 --> 08:26.605
because pockets would mean
you weren't rich enough

08:26.607 --> 08:28.540
to pay people
to carry your stuff.

08:28.542 --> 08:30.609
And for the average poor man,

08:30.611 --> 08:33.712
wide legged baggy trousers
with deep pockets

08:33.714 --> 08:36.915
you could keep
all your peasant stuff in.

08:36.917 --> 08:39.618
And as the spirit of equality
swept Europe,

08:39.620 --> 08:42.354
so did the trend
for baggier, pocketier pants.

08:42.356 --> 08:45.490
Fill your pockets with the songs
of angry men...

08:45.492 --> 08:48.527
(crowd cheering)

08:48.529 --> 08:51.229
...and you're keys.

08:51.231 --> 08:55.200
Pockets were in many
ways a revolutionary idea,

08:55.202 --> 08:58.436
but not one deemed appropriate
for women.

08:58.438 --> 09:01.206
You see, people thought it would
make them too independent.

09:01.208 --> 09:05.010
It was considered unladylike
to carry anything larger

09:05.012 --> 09:06.545
than a teeny tiny purse.

09:06.547 --> 09:09.314
M'lady, in this fight
for liberty,

09:09.316 --> 09:12.350
I shall carry everything
you need to function in society.

09:12.352 --> 09:15.987
¶¶

09:15.989 --> 09:18.290
Some women fought back
in the late 1800s

09:18.292 --> 09:21.159
wearing extremely
baggy pants with pockets

09:21.161 --> 09:24.229
as part of the rational
dress movement.

09:24.231 --> 09:25.564
Stop!
(music stops)

09:25.566 --> 09:26.731
Pocket time!

09:26.733 --> 09:29.334
(crowd cheers, music playing)

09:29.336 --> 09:31.136
You can't touch this.

09:31.138 --> 09:34.472
As in my new found sense
of independence.

09:34.474 --> 09:37.409
But men of the era couldn't wrap
their narrow-minded brains

09:37.411 --> 09:40.078
around it,
newspaper editorials at the time

09:40.080 --> 09:42.147
speculated that the pockets
of the new woman

09:42.149 --> 09:43.515
were a weird fetish.

09:43.517 --> 09:45.150
Whatever floats
your boats ladies,

09:45.152 --> 09:49.154
but I think having pockets makes
you some kind of sex freak.

09:49.156 --> 09:51.890
And women have had
to continue to fight

09:51.892 --> 09:54.659
for more practical clothing
throughout history.

09:56.396 --> 09:59.030
In 1954, Christian Dior,
one of fashion's

09:59.032 --> 10:02.233
most influential designers said,
"Men have pockets

10:02.235 --> 10:05.070
to keep things in.
Women, for decoration."

10:05.072 --> 10:08.239
Even today, when women's
clothing has pockets,

10:08.241 --> 10:11.209
the cuts are typically
too tight to be useful.

10:11.211 --> 10:13.812
One study compared
women's and men's pants

10:13.814 --> 10:16.648
across 20 brands and found that
women's pockets

10:16.650 --> 10:18.984
were half the size of men's.

10:18.986 --> 10:22.520
I mean, where would
the pockets even go?

10:22.522 --> 10:24.189
That is so unfair.

10:24.191 --> 10:26.391
Yup. Not having
practical clothing

10:26.393 --> 10:28.627
limits women's ability
to function.

10:28.629 --> 10:32.831
I mean, why can't
I look amazeballs and have
a place to put my phone?

10:32.833 --> 10:35.867
Yeah, you know, men's pockets
don't hold everything either.

10:35.869 --> 10:37.202
I got stuffed here.

10:37.204 --> 10:39.604
Well, there's
an answer for that.

10:39.606 --> 10:41.740
A purse!
Perfect!

10:41.742 --> 10:44.075
But, wait,
I'm a guy, is this okay?

10:44.077 --> 10:47.846
It should be, but everyone
acts like having a bag
is a girl thing.

10:47.848 --> 10:49.280
Like in that
"Friends" episode.

10:49.282 --> 10:51.182
It's got compartments
for all your stuff:

10:51.184 --> 10:53.418
your wallet,
your keys,
you're address book.

10:53.420 --> 10:54.452
Your makeup.

10:56.089 --> 10:59.357
Yeah, stuff like this
gets stuck in guys' heads

10:59.359 --> 11:01.693
and makes us too embarrassed
to deviate from what's

11:01.695 --> 11:03.228
supposed to be "manly."

11:03.230 --> 11:06.031
I've lived in fear that Ross
was gonna yell at me.

11:06.033 --> 11:09.467
But that's stupid.
Ross sucks!

11:11.772 --> 11:13.571
(chanting)
Give ladies pockets!

11:13.573 --> 11:15.907
(chanting)
Let men have purses.

11:15.909 --> 11:18.543
(quietly)
I agree, but less obnoxiously.

11:19.813 --> 11:20.879
All right, time to go.

11:20.881 --> 11:23.548
Oh, what?
Is this about my purse?

11:23.550 --> 11:25.817
No, man.
It's about your personality.

11:25.819 --> 11:27.252
Let's go.

11:27.254 --> 11:30.722
Pshh! Who wants to spend all
night in a crowded club anyways?

11:30.724 --> 11:32.190
I thought we did.

11:32.192 --> 11:33.358
But if you guys
don't wanna dance,

11:33.360 --> 11:35.060
I guess we could grab
a drink somewhere.

11:35.062 --> 11:36.261
I could really use one.

11:36.263 --> 11:39.130
Oh, I know a place that makes
great Shirley Temples.

11:39.132 --> 11:41.966
Whatever you guys want,
first round's on me.

11:41.968 --> 11:44.269
Actually, it'll probably
have to just be one round.

11:44.271 --> 11:46.037
Yeah, I have MMA
in the morning.

11:46.039 --> 11:48.673
Plus, alcohol
is basically poison,

11:48.675 --> 11:50.375
but I can try and forget that
for a night.

11:50.377 --> 11:51.676
