in the late '90s.

12:58.345 --> 13:01.045
(loud music playing)
And over the next two decades
this approach

13:01.047 --> 13:03.348
became a sonic standard.

13:03.350 --> 13:06.785
Modern restaurant design has
made the issue even worse.

13:06.787 --> 13:09.287
the stark post industrial
aesthetic of today

13:09.289 --> 13:12.824
leaves us with few
of the sound dampeners
restaurants used to rely on.

13:12.826 --> 13:15.593
Tablecloths, carpets, drapes,
and velvet booths

13:15.595 --> 13:18.129
have been replaced by
sonically reflective surfaces

13:18.131 --> 13:21.166
like polished metal,
concrete, and glass.

13:21.168 --> 13:23.968
One study found that louder
music increased

13:23.970 --> 13:26.704
and even sped up
alcohol consumption.

13:26.706 --> 13:30.942
But save it for the club,
not my chicken club.

13:30.944 --> 13:34.179
(loud music, loud chatter)
I mean, why did you think this
was such a good idea?! Huh?

13:34.181 --> 13:35.180
(people shushing)

13:35.182 --> 13:37.982
Oh. Oops, sorry.
My bad.

13:37.984 --> 13:39.617
I'm just gonna
go eat take out at home.

13:41.254 --> 13:43.621
I am so sorry about this.
We will have one drink

13:43.623 --> 13:45.123
and then we'll
call it a night.

13:45.125 --> 13:47.258
Uh, I'm actually having
a great time.

13:47.260 --> 13:48.326
Are you not having fun?

13:48.328 --> 13:51.262
Okay!
Shirley Temple for Adam.

13:51.264 --> 13:53.765
And Emily, not to be
cheesy or whatever,

13:53.767 --> 13:55.867
but in honor of our
college years,

13:55.869 --> 13:58.870
I got us
white wine spritzers.

13:58.872 --> 14:01.506
Remember when we used to have
like ten of these in a night?

14:01.508 --> 14:03.942
(laughing)
Oh, man, I...

14:03.944 --> 14:05.109
definitely don't.

14:05.111 --> 14:06.644
Cheers! (giggles)

14:06.646 --> 14:08.913
(glasses clink)

14:08.915 --> 14:10.481
Adam, are you sure you
don't want a real drink?

14:10.483 --> 14:12.517
Can't ruin wine.

14:12.519 --> 14:14.686
A glass a day is good
for your heart or whatever.

14:14.688 --> 14:17.488
No, thanks.
I'm good with my Shirley T.

14:17.490 --> 14:19.357
And actually,
the alcohol industry

14:19.359 --> 14:21.459
just wants you to think that
moderate drinking is healthy

14:21.461 --> 14:24.529
to distract you
from the indisputable
health risks.

14:24.531 --> 14:25.730
Oh, yeah.

14:25.732 --> 14:27.765
No, no, no.
You guys are both wrong.

14:27.767 --> 14:31.002
I read you'll actually die
sooner if you don't drink.

14:31.004 --> 14:32.437
There have been studies.

14:32.439 --> 14:34.973
Yeah, people love
citing that stat.

14:34.975 --> 14:36.507
But the problem is...

14:36.509 --> 14:38.943
it's not true.

14:38.945 --> 14:41.813
The media is constantly
telling us

14:41.815 --> 14:44.549
that non drinkers actually have
higher mortality rates

14:44.551 --> 14:46.017
than moderate drinkers.

14:46.019 --> 14:48.319
Yeah, see, it's right
on the graph.

14:48.321 --> 14:50.822
Well, the problem with studies
that show this result

14:50.824 --> 14:53.591
is they're based
on some very flawed data.

14:53.593 --> 14:55.593
It turns out that
if you take a closer look

14:55.595 --> 14:57.528
at the cohort
of non drinkers,

14:57.530 --> 14:58.997
many of them
are less healthy

14:58.999 --> 15:01.332
for completely
unrelated reasons.

15:01.334 --> 15:04.335
Some simply can't
afford to drink

15:04.337 --> 15:06.571
or pay for health insurance.

15:06.573 --> 15:09.140
Others already suffer
from medical conditions

15:09.142 --> 15:10.842
that prevent them
from drinking.

15:10.844 --> 15:12.877
(sad trombone sound)

15:12.879 --> 15:16.314
And some are former drinkers
who've already suffered

15:16.316 --> 15:18.549
the negative health
effects of alcohol abuse.

15:18.551 --> 15:21.886
If the studies had taken this
skewing effect into account,

15:21.888 --> 15:24.355
the graph would
have looked like this

15:24.357 --> 15:26.858
indicating that there
are zero health advantages

15:26.860 --> 15:28.927
to being a moderate drinker.

15:28.929 --> 15:30.161
Seriously?

15:30.163 --> 15:32.263
(slurring)
No, but wait.
Hold up.

15:32.265 --> 15:33.932
It gets wor-- worse.

15:33.934 --> 15:36.868
Whoa, Emily,
you're already plastered.

15:36.870 --> 15:39.504
Yeah, bitch!
I barely drink anymore.

15:39.506 --> 15:41.005
Whoo!

15:41.007 --> 15:42.740
Becks, truth is...

15:42.742 --> 15:45.243
drinking is not only
not good for you,

15:45.245 --> 15:49.113
it's actually like super bad
for you healthy times.

15:49.115 --> 15:51.749
What about all the
antioxidants in wine?

15:51.751 --> 15:53.084
Those fight cancer.

15:53.086 --> 15:56.454
Snopes! There is actually
no conclusive evidence

15:56.456 --> 15:58.923
that antioxidants
in wine do anything.

15:58.925 --> 16:00.124
(Adam)
That's true.

16:00.126 --> 16:01.826
But the real reason this myth
is messed up,

16:01.828 --> 16:04.095
is that far
from preventing cancer,

16:04.097 --> 16:05.430
there's actually
considerable evidence

16:05.432 --> 16:08.199
that drinking alcohol
risks causing it.

16:08.201 --> 16:11.636
Alcohol is a Group 1
known carcinogen.

16:11.638 --> 16:13.738
In fact,
the World Health Organization

16:13.740 --> 16:16.941
attributes over half a million
cancer deaths worldwide

16:16.943 --> 16:19.510
to alcohol consumption
every year.

16:19.512 --> 16:23.681
(slurring)
Plus, alcohol is special
extra kind of cancerous...

16:23.683 --> 16:27.452
for ladies! Whoo!
Whoo!

16:27.454 --> 16:30.021
Why are you "whooing?"
This is not a time to "whoo."

16:30.023 --> 16:31.222
Definitely not.

16:31.224 --> 16:34.659
Ooh, I am kind of obnoxious
when I drink.

16:34.661 --> 16:36.761
Becks, look.

16:36.763 --> 16:38.963
Every cancer diagnosis
is different,

16:38.965 --> 16:42.266
but studies show that booze
is a factor in an estimated

16:42.268 --> 16:45.937
15% of breast cancer
cases annually.

16:45.939 --> 16:48.673
That's 6,000
deaths per year.

16:48.675 --> 16:50.708
Yes, thank you.
Please cut me off.

16:50.710 --> 16:52.443
Now, to be clear,

16:52.445 --> 16:54.912
this doesn't mean that avoiding
alcohol prevents cancer,

16:54.914 --> 16:57.582
or that if you've received
a breast cancer diagnosis

16:57.584 --> 16:58.850
your choices are to blame.

16:58.852 --> 17:01.085
The truth is
no type of cancer

17:01.087 --> 17:03.521
can be pegged
to just one behavioral quality.

17:03.523 --> 17:04.956
But there's no denying

17:04.958 --> 17:07.658
that drinking comes
with certain health risks.

17:07.660 --> 17:10.461
So isn't it weird that
we never talk about it?

17:10.463 --> 17:12.930
I mean, we all know
that smoking is bad for us,

17:12.932 --> 17:15.366
but 70%
of Americans

17:15.368 --> 17:19.203
have no idea that alcohol
can cause cancer too.

17:19.205 --> 17:22.306
I sure didn't.
Why doesn't anyone
talk about this?

17:22.308 --> 17:25.777
Because Big Booze has spent
decades covering up the data

17:25.779 --> 17:28.079
with their own bad science.

17:28.081 --> 17:30.948
Just like Big Tobacco
used to do for cigarettes.

17:30.950 --> 17:33.518
For instance,
in 1994,

17:33.520 --> 17:36.621
the Distilled Spirits Council
actually hired a scientist

17:36.623 --> 17:38.856
from tobacco powerhouse
Philip Morris

17:38.858 --> 17:41.459
and paid for a study
that disputed the link

17:41.461 --> 17:43.661
between alcohol
and breast cancer.

17:43.663 --> 17:44.762
(slide whistle)

17:44.764 --> 17:46.531
(slurring)
In fact m--
Big Booze funds

17:46.533 --> 17:48.366
most studies on alcohol.

17:48.368 --> 17:50.501
And not just the ones
that dispute harm.

17:50.503 --> 17:53.104
They also spend
billions on research

17:53.106 --> 17:56.107
that "supposably" shows
"health benefits."

17:56.109 --> 17:57.842
Beers are on me.

17:57.844 --> 18:00.311
And so are the studies that
say they're good for you.

18:00.313 --> 18:03.948
Big Booze is so dedicated
to controlling how we perceive

18:03.950 --> 18:06.818
drinking in the US they've
lobbied against measures

18:06.820 --> 18:08.986
that might
reduce problem drinking

18:08.988 --> 18:11.522
like warning labels
and sales taxes.

18:12.759 --> 18:14.092
Pshh!

18:14.094 --> 18:16.427
Whoo!
Nickel shots!

18:16.429 --> 18:18.996
And don't forget the massive
amounts of money

18:18.998 --> 18:22.834
they spend pouring alcohol
advertising down our throats.

18:22.836 --> 18:24.235
<i> Cheers!</i>

18:24.237 --> 18:27.405
And now Americans are drinking
way more than we used to.

18:27.407 --> 18:29.340
The number of adults
that binge drink

18:29.342 --> 18:33.711
at least once a week could be as
high as 30 million.

18:33.713 --> 18:36.814
Okay, guys. I get that this
is all very important, but--

18:36.816 --> 18:38.649
(slurring)
Oh, my God, you have
to meet my friend.

18:40.286 --> 18:42.220
Becks, this is who
I was telling you about.

18:42.222 --> 18:45.189
Doctor Timothy Naimi,
an epidemiologist

18:45.191 --> 18:47.792
who's worked on alcohol
task forces at the CDC

18:47.794 --> 18:49.527
and the National Institutes
of Health.

18:49.529 --> 18:52.430
(Naimi)
Becks, although alcohol
is marketed to us

18:52.432 --> 18:54.298
like it's part
of a healthy lifestyle,

18:54.300 --> 18:56.367
the idea that there's
health benefits

18:56.369 --> 18:58.469
from moderate drinking
is probably crap.

18:58.471 --> 19:00.638
Most people's
"moderate drinking"

19:00.640 --> 19:03.741
actually exceeds the dietary
guideline suggested limits

19:03.743 --> 19:06.644
of no more than one drink
in a day for women,

19:06.646 --> 19:08.212
and no more than
two drinks in a day for men.

19:08.214 --> 19:11.282
That's not to say that people
shouldn't enjoy alcohol at all,

19:11.284 --> 19:13.251
but what we know
is that if you drink,

19:13.253 --> 19:15.286
drinking less is better
for your health.

19:15.288 --> 19:17.688
Well, now it feels like
I don't have a choice.

19:17.690 --> 19:19.891
You're basically like,
"Yeah, go on, keep drinking...

19:19.893 --> 19:21.192
if you're an idiot."

19:21.194 --> 19:23.327
No, Becks,
we're not judging you.

19:23.329 --> 19:25.763
It's fun to do things
that are bad for us

19:25.765 --> 19:27.031
every once in a while.

19:27.033 --> 19:29.767
We just shouldn't pretend
that they're healthy.

19:29.769 --> 19:32.036
Just like how I write in the
margins of books, even though

19:32.038 --> 19:34.205
I know it lowers
their resale value.

19:34.207 --> 19:35.740
But it's just
such a rush!

19:35.742 --> 19:37.542
(Naimi)
Drinking has become
so normalized

19:37.544 --> 19:39.010
as part of American culture.

19:39.012 --> 19:42.513
And we feel like, well, as long
as I'm not a "alcoholic"

19:42.515 --> 19:44.315
I can pretty much drink
whatever I want.

19:44.317 --> 19:47.151
The fact is, is that health
professionals agree

19:47.153 --> 19:51.489
that risky drinking
exists across a wide spectrum
of consumption.

19:51.491 --> 19:55.860
Only 5% of Americans meet
the medical definition
for alcohol dependency,

19:55.862 --> 19:59.664
but it's important to know
that about 30% of Americans

19:59.666 --> 20:01.999
drink in ways that clearly
increase their risk

20:02.001 --> 20:04.669
for a variety
of alcohol related consequences.

20:04.671 --> 20:06.370
(slurring)
And the "shtigma" of alcoholism

20:06.372 --> 20:09.907
makes people less willing
to examine their own

20:09.909 --> 20:12.210
alcohol consumption
and cut back,

20:12.212 --> 20:15.213
because they don't want to think
they have a drinking problem.

20:15.215 --> 20:17.915
Okay, it sorta feels like
you're saying

20:17.917 --> 20:19.517
I have a drinking problem.

20:19.519 --> 20:21.052
Oh, no, no, no.

20:21.054 --> 20:23.554
So, all I'm saying is--
Actually,
you know what it is?

20:23.556 --> 20:25.590
You don't have an issue
with my drinking,

20:25.592 --> 20:28.392
you have an issue
with me, okay.

20:28.394 --> 20:30.428
Doctor Naimi,
really nice to meet you.

20:30.430 --> 20:32.029
So sorry you got
dragged into this.

20:32.031 --> 20:33.431
(Emily)
Oh, no, Becks.
Wait!

20:33.433 --> 20:35.666
Honestly, Emily, if you didn't
want to come out tonight,

20:35.668 --> 20:37.201
why didn't you just say so?

20:37.203 --> 20:39.704
(slurring)
I don't know, I mean,
we were best friends in college.

20:39.706 --> 20:41.005
I kinda had to.

20:41.007 --> 20:43.274
Had to?! Is that supposed
to make me feel better?

20:43.276 --> 20:45.042
I mean, are we even
friends anymore?

20:45.044 --> 20:47.211
Oh, actually,
now that you mention it,

20:47.213 --> 20:48.646
according to this one study
that I read--

20:48.648 --> 20:50.648
Oh, my God!
Stop!

20:57.023 --> 20:58.623
I wouldn't say totally.

20:58.625 --> 21:00.191
Becks, we owe you
an apology.

21:00.193 --> 21:01.626
You know,
between you and me,

21:01.628 --> 21:03.861
Emily can kind of get carried
away with the ruining.

21:03.863 --> 21:05.763
I learned it
from watching you!

21:05.765 --> 21:09.567
Actually, you've always
sort of been like this, okay?

21:09.569 --> 21:13.037
Except now with snapping
and learning ghosts.

21:13.039 --> 21:15.006
But if I'm being
totally honest,

21:15.008 --> 21:17.541
you've always made me feel like
I'm too dumb for you.

21:17.543 --> 21:19.977
Well, if I'm being
honest-honest,

21:19.979 --> 21:22.947
you've always made me feel
like you're too cool for me.

21:22.949 --> 21:25.716
Becks, if you can handle
one more ruin,

21:25.718 --> 21:27.985
I think the study
Emily mentioned,

21:27.987 --> 21:29.820
might actually help both
of you feel better.

21:29.822 --> 21:32.223
How? By making me realize that
Emily is a big know-it-all

21:32.225 --> 21:33.924
and doesn't want
to be friends with me?

21:33.926 --> 21:34.825
Exactly.

21:34.827 --> 21:36.093
Many studies have shown

21:36.095 --> 21:38.996
that up to half of friendships
aren't reciprocal.

21:38.998 --> 21:42.266
So, maybe you were never
friends to begin with.

21:42.268 --> 21:43.668
I think we were
friends at some point,

21:43.670 --> 21:45.436
but we've definitely
drifted apart.

21:45.438 --> 21:48.005
Well, that's
totally natural too.

21:48.007 --> 21:50.007
According to an
anthropological concept

21:50.009 --> 21:53.277
called Dunbar's Number,
the human brain can only handle

21:53.279 --> 21:55.346
five close relationships.

21:55.348 --> 21:57.948
(laughter)

21:59.852 --> 22:00.918
(balloon deflating sound)

22:00.920 --> 22:02.586
I guess I didn't
want to admit it,

22:02.588 --> 22:04.588
but we're not friends.

22:04.590 --> 22:07.158
And we haven't
been for awhile.

22:07.160 --> 22:09.160
I mean, I didn't even
want to go to your wedding.

22:09.162 --> 22:10.661
Aw...

22:10.663 --> 22:13.130
I didn't even want
to invite you.

22:13.132 --> 22:15.066
You know, this made me
feel so much better.

22:15.068 --> 22:17.368
Em, see you never.

22:17.370 --> 22:21.072
Adam, we are definitely
hanging out again.
You cool as shit.

22:23.142 --> 22:24.275
Whoo!

22:25.611 --> 22:27.311
There we go.
There we go.
Yeah.

22:27.313 --> 22:30.715
(slurring)
Well, looks like
we ruined everyone's night.

22:30.717 --> 22:32.350
Including our own.

22:32.352 --> 22:34.218
Yeah, I had a blast.

22:34.220 --> 22:37.121
By the way, you know,
eating doesn't actually
sober you up, right?

22:37.123 --> 22:38.189
Ah!

22:38.191 --> 22:40.124
Dang it.
Come on. All right.

22:40.126 --> 22:41.158
You know what?
You can't drive.

22:41.160 --> 22:42.727
I'm putting you
on a bus.

22:44.997 --> 22:49.033
Mmm.
My head feels terrible.

22:49.035 --> 22:51.669
And my stomach...
(stomach bubbling)

22:51.671 --> 22:54.905
And my... elbow?

22:54.907 --> 22:58.876
Ugh, I drank way too much
last night.

22:58.878 --> 23:00.911
And what makes me
feel even worse,

23:00.913 --> 23:03.581
is that there's
no way to cure it

23:03.583 --> 23:07.017
because science doesn't really
know why we get hangovers

23:07.019 --> 23:08.452
in the first place.

23:08.454 --> 23:11.122
You might think that your
heinous headache

23:11.124 --> 23:13.924
and needling nausea
are caused by something like

23:13.926 --> 23:15.192
electrolyte imbalance,

23:15.194 --> 23:18.829
but even if your gam-gam swears
by Gatorade,

23:18.831 --> 23:21.999
recent research
hasn't shown any correlation

23:22.001 --> 23:25.169
between hangover symptoms
and electrolyte imbalance.

23:25.171 --> 23:27.204
So maybe it's low blood sugar.

23:27.206 --> 23:28.239
Except no!

23:28.241 --> 23:30.174
Sugar doesn't help cure
a hangover,

23:30.176 --> 23:32.009
so we know it's not that.

23:32.011 --> 23:36.213
And you certainly can't fix your
hangover with hair of the dog.

23:36.215 --> 23:37.948
That's a straight up myth.

23:37.950 --> 23:41.552
Truth is... we don't know
how we get hungover,

23:41.554 --> 23:44.121
because we don't entirely
understand how we get drunk

23:44.123 --> 23:45.389
in the first place.

23:45.391 --> 23:48.159
The most likely theory
is that hangovers

23:48.161 --> 23:50.895
are an inflammatory response
like what happens

23:50.897 --> 23:52.530
when we get an infection.

23:52.532 --> 23:55.299
You can try taking an
anti-inflammatory pain killer

23:55.301 --> 23:58.803
like ibuprofen, but those can
upset your stomach

23:58.805 --> 24:02.173
which is already pretty unhappy.
(bubbling)

24:02.175 --> 24:04.642
The only surefire cure
for a hangover

24:04.644 --> 24:06.610
is never drinking
in the first place.

24:06.612 --> 24:10.581
But if you do wind up knee-deep
in tequila sunrises--

24:10.583 --> 24:13.984
(whispers)
Oh, goddamnit, just the name.

24:13.986 --> 24:17.922
All you can do is drink a lotta
water and try to sleep it off.

24:17.924 --> 24:20.391
Which is what
I'm going to do.

24:21.494 --> 24:23.093
Right here.

24:24.897 --> 24:26.464
Can someone
take my mic back?

24:26.466 --> 24:28.699
I don't want everyone
to hear me snoring.

24:30.603 --> 24:32.169
Eh, who cares?

24:32.171 --> 24:33.170
(snoring)
